         <div type="comments">
            <p>
               <note type="parallels"><bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>115f</citedRange></bibl>.; <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch554"/></note>
               <note corresp="#a2" type="lingcomment">Note that the iterative adverb Skt. <hi>tat tat</hi> (11d) is translated by the corresponding TB adverb and with the emphatic particle <hi>-k</hi> in order to render the expressive force of the repetition (and not simply by <hi>tu tu</hi>).</note>
               <note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">One should restore <hi>(k<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>ce) k<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>ce</hi> translating Skt. <hi>yad yaj jahāti kāmānāṃ</hi> (11c).</note>
               <note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">The verbal form ending with <hi>-tär</hi> ought to be restored as <hi>riñiträ</hi>. The translation of the pāda 12b Skt. <hi>sarvakāmāṃ parityajet</hi> was certainly <hi>po yśelmeṃ päst riñiträ</hi>. The correct Sanskrit form should be <hi>sarvakāmaparityāgī</hi> (12c). <hi>sukha</hi> at the end of the line is the beginning of Skt. <hi>sukham edhate</hi> (12d).</note>
               <note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Note that the Sanskrit text has the reading <hi>anusaraṃ</hi> in all manuscripts. The spelling <hi>-an<hi rend="subscript">\</hi></hi> is consistent with the spelling <hi>-am<hi rend="subscript">\</hi></hi> met in other instances in this same manuscript. At the end of the line <hi>na</hi> is the first word of the pāda 13a. Very tentatively one can interpret the remains of the akṣaras at the beginning of the line as reflecting a 3.sg.mid. verbal form matching Skt. <hi>edhate</hi> (12d), possibly <hi>(yän)[m](ās)[tä]r</hi> ‘he obtains’.</note>
               <note corresp="#b2" type="lingcomment">The Sanskrit aorist <hi>adhi-agāt</hi> at the end of 13b is literary translated by the preterite <hi>yonmasa</hi> even though (as is clear from the context) the Sanskrit form has a gnomic value.</note>
               <note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">At the end of the line <hi>tu</hi> ought to be completed to <hi>tumeṃ</hi> matching Skt. <hi>tataḥ</hi> at the beginning of pāda 13c.</note>
               <note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">At the end of the line one should restore the perlative singular <hi>aiśamñesa</hi> translating Skt. <hi>prajñayā</hi> (13d).</note>
               <note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">The complete Sanskrit pāda 14b is: <hi>na hi kāmair vitṛpyate</hi>.</note>
            </p>
